<ContentPage
  title="About LazyTools — Why We Built Privacy-First Tools | LazyTools"
  description="LazyTools is a growing collection of free online tools that process everything in your browser. Learn why we built it and the principles behind it."
  heading="About LazyTools"
>
  <p>
    LazyTools is a growing collection of free online utilities — unit converters, calculators, file tools and
    more — built on one non-negotiable principle: <strong>your data never leaves your device.</strong>
  </p>

  <h2>Why we built this</h2>
  <p>
    Every day, millions of people upload private files — contracts, photos, IDs, financial documents — to random
    "free online tools" websites, trusting a stranger's server with their data in exchange for a simple conversion
    or compression. That trade never made sense to us. Modern browsers are powerful enough to do all of this work
    locally, so that's how every LazyTools utility is built. Read
    <a href="/how-it-works/">how it works</a> for the technical details.
  </p>

  <h2>Our principles</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Private by architecture.</strong> Tools run in your browser. There are no processing servers, so there's nothing to trust — you can verify it.</li>
    <li><strong>Free means free.</strong> No sign-up walls, no file-size bait, no "3 conversions per day" games.</li>
    <li><strong>Fast and honest.</strong> Instant results, exact formulas shown, sources cited, limitations stated plainly.</li>
    <li><strong>No AI gimmicks.</strong> We build deterministic tools that give exact answers — the kind of jobs where a chatbot's approximation isn't good enough.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Editorial &amp; accuracy standards</h2>
  <p>
    Every page on LazyTools is built and reviewed by a person, one page at a time — nothing is
    mass-generated. The standards we hold ourselves to:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Exact, sourced numbers.</strong> Conversion factors follow the official international definitions (NIST/BIPM and equivalent bodies); formulas are shown on the page so you can check the math yourself.</li>
    <li><strong>No invented facts.</strong> Blog guides cite their sources, and if something is an estimate or has caveats, we say so on the page.</li>
    <li><strong>Honest dates.</strong> Published and updated dates reflect real changes, not cosmetic refreshes.</li>
    <li><strong>Every page earns its place.</strong> A page only exists if it answers a question no other page here answers — and pages that stop being useful get improved or removed, not left to rot.</li>
    <li><strong>Verifiable claims.</strong> The whole codebase is open source, so "nothing is uploaded" isn't a promise — it's inspectable.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Spotted an error? <a href="/contact/">Tell us</a> — corrections ship in the next weekly release.
  </p>

  <h2>Who's behind LazyTools</h2>
  <p>
    LazyTools.io is part of the projects portfolio of <a href="https://synth88.com" rel="noopener">Synth88 Labs Inc.</a>
    The entire site is developed in the open as an
    <a href="https://github.com/Synth88Labs/lazytools.io" rel="noopener">MIT-licensed open-source project on GitHub</a> —
    you can inspect every line that touches your data, follow the roadmap, and even reuse the tool code in
    your own website.
  </p>

  <h2>Contact</h2>
  <p>
    Questions, ideas or a tool you wish existed? <a href="/contact/">Get in touch</a> — tool requests genuinely
    shape the roadmap.
  </p>
